#{\footnote versioninfo}${\footnote Version information}K{\footnote Version information}
{\f4\fs30\b Version information}
\plain \f4\fs20
\par
\par
This help file relates to version 2.0 of the Nonogram solver program (NONOGRAM.EXE). This version was released on 20/12/1993.\par
\par
This version incorporates a superior user interface over previous versions. A new button bar and a status bar have been incorporated as well. \par
\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Also see
\par\plain\f4\fs20\uldb
Contents\plain \v\f4 main_contents\plain\par \f4\fs20\uldb
\page

#{\footnote preferences}${\footnote Preferences}K{\footnote Preferences}
{\f4\fs30\b Preferences}
\plain \f4\fs20
\par
\par
The following options can be selected in the preferences dialog box.\par
\par
Solve confirmation - selecting this option enables a popup dialog box after a solution attempt.\par
Load confirmation - selecting this option enables a popup dialog box after a file has been loaded.\par
Tool bar - selecting this option enables the tool bar.\par
Status bar - selecting this option enables the status bar.\par
Save on exit - selecting this option saves all user set options when the program exits.\par
\par
\par\f4\fs24\b
Also see
\par\plain\f4\fs20\uldb
Contents\plain \v\f4 main_contents\plain\par \f4\fs20\uldb
\page

#{\footnote introduction}${\footnote Introducing Nonograms}K{\footnote Introducing Nonograms;What is a Nonogram?;Nonograms}
{\f4\fs30\b Introducing Nonograms}
\plain \f4\fs20
\par
\par
\plain \ul\f4\fs20 Nonogram's\plain \ul\v\f4\fs20 typnono\plain \f4\fs20  belong to the grid family of puzzles and are composed of a grid of squares, which can either be fully filled with one colour or left blank. (The Nonogram Solver for Windows uses grey to represent the unfilled squares and white to represent the filled squares.) Basic numerical data about the arrangement of the filled and unfilled squares is given, and it is up to the user to fill in the squares.\par
\par
The Nonogram Solver uses a variety of algorithmns to obtain a solution all of which can be tailored by the user. How to do so is given in the \plain \uldb\f4\fs20 Display Options\plain \uldb\v\f4\fs20 display\plain \f4\fs20  and the \plain \uldb\f4\fs20 Solution Options\plain \uldb\v\f4\fs20 solution\plain \f4\fs20  help entries.\par
\par
In order to perform a conversion, the program must be given an appropriate data file - see \plain \uldb\f4\fs20 Data Files\plain \uldb\v\f4\fs20 datafiles\plain \f4\fs20  for more information.\par
\par
\par\b\f4\fs24
Also See
\par\plain\f4\fs20\uldb
Contents\plain \v\f4\ main_contents\plain\par \f4\fs20\uldb
\page 

#{\footnote datafiles}${\footnote Data files}K{\footnote Data files;Data format}
{\f4\fs30\b Data files}
\plain \f4\fs20
\par
\par
Data files must be in a plain ASCII format (such as those produced using NOTEPAD etc)\par
\par
The format is of one title line, followed by the puzzle data. The puzzle will be in the form of a MxN grid and the data for the side of M must be entered first, followed by that for the side of N. \par
\par
For example:\par
\par \f0\fs18
White Rabbit Nonogram\tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Title line\par \f0\fs18
1 2 10 2\tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - First line of data out of block of N\par \f0\fs18
2 3 2 4\tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Second line of data out of block of N\par \f0\fs18
3 4 1 6\tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Third line of data out of block of N\par \f0\fs18
: : : :  : \tab \tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Another (M+N-4) rows of data\par \f0\fs18
4 5 3 11\tab \tab \tab \_ \f8\fs20 - Nth line of data out of block of N\par \f0\fs18
\par
Also please note that all Nonogram data files should be saved with the extension '.NGM'. Although the DOS version of the Nonogram Solver will only recognise data files with this extension, the Windows version can read in other data files.\par
\par
\par\b\f4\fs24
Also See
\par\plain \uldb\f4\fs20
Contents\plain \v\f4\fs20 main_contents\plain 
\page 

#{\footnote solution}${\footnote Solution options}K{\footnote Solution options;VARS}
{\f4\fs30\b Solution options}
\plain \f4\fs20
\par
\par
Various solution options are available. Choose Options|Solutions to access the options dialog box. By toggling the status of the check boxes it is possible to enable/disable various solution options - it is also possible to alter the size of the \plain \uldb\f4\fs20 VARS\uldb\v\f4\fs20 vars \plain\f4\fs20  array.\par
\par
\par\b\f4\fs24
Also See
